\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Clinically-Inspired Reasoning Pipelines:
\f0\b0  To mitigate the risk of unconstrained and erroneous outputs, the LLM's reasoning process can be structured to follow established clinical workflows. This forces the model to "think" more like a clinician, improving the coherence and safety of its conclusions.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The 
\f1\b MedPlan
\f0\b0  framework, for example, implements a two-stage pipeline inspired by the ubiquitous SOAP (Subjective, Objective, Assessment, Plan) note format. In the first stage, the LLM generates a clinical 
\f2\i Assessment
\f0\i0  based only on the Subjective and Objective data. Only after this diagnostic step is complete does the system proceed to the second stage: formulating a 
\f2\i Plan
\f0\i0  based on the now-established assessment.
\fs32 \super 22
\fs24 \nosupersub  This sequential process prevents the model from prematurely jumping to a treatment plan without a clear diagnostic rationale.\
\ls3\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f3 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Similarly, the 
\f1\b MedGellan
\f0\b0  framework employs a Bayesian-inspired inference process. It first establishes a prior hypothesis based on initial information (e.g., a triage note) and then systematically updates this hypothesis with new evidence (e.g., a chest radiology report) to arrive at a final, evidence-grounded guidance summary.
\fs32 \super 23
\fs24 \nosupersub \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG):
\f0\b0  This architectural pattern is arguably the most critical for ensuring safety and traceability. A standard LLM generates responses based on patterns learned during training, a process that is internal and opaque. A RAG-based system, by contrast, does not rely solely on this parametric memory. Before generating any text, it first retrieves relevant information from a trusted, external knowledge base. This knowledge base could include the patient's own longitudinal EHR, established clinical practice guidelines, institutional protocols, and drug interaction databases.
\fs32 \super 24
\fs24 \nosupersub  The LLM is then prompted to synthesize the retrieved information to generate the updated documentation. This approach has two profound benefits: it dramatically reduces the likelihood of hallucination by grounding the output in factual source documents, and it makes the system's output inherently \uc0\u8232 
\f1\b auditable
\f0\b0 . Each generated statement can be traced back to the specific source documents that were retrieved to create it.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Multimodal Integration:
\f0\b0  Clinical decision-making relies on more than just text. A truly adaptive system must be able to reason over a combination of data modalities, including text (notes, reports), images (radiology, pathology), and structured data (lab values, vital signs).
\fs32 \super 25
\fs24 \nosupersub  Advanced multimodal architectures accomplish this by using modality-specific encoders to process each type of input, a fusion layer to align these different data streams into a unified embedding, and a final LLM to perform contextual understanding and generate the output.
\fs32 \super 26
\fs24 \nosupersub \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
