\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 4.2 The Specter of Algorithmic Bias in Personalized Records\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \
One of the most insidious risks of AI in healthcare is its potential to perpetuate and even amplify existing societal biases, leading to inequitable documentation and care.
\fs32 \super 10
\fs24 \nosupersub  AI models learn from the data they are trained on, and if that data reflects historical or systemic biases, the model will codify those biases into its decision-making logic.
\fs32 \super 17
\fs24 \nosupersub  This can manifest in two primary forms of harm:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Disparate Impact Risk:
\f0\b0  This occurs when an algorithm's application results in different and less favorable outcomes for a protected group, even if the algorithm appears neutral on its face. The canonical example in healthcare involves an algorithm widely used in the US to predict which patients would benefit from high-risk care management programs. The algorithm used a patient's past healthcare costs as a proxy for their level of health need. Because less money is historically spent on Black patients due to a complex mix of factors including systemic racism and unequal access to care, the algorithm systematically assigned them lower risk scores than White patients with the same level of sickness. This created an unjustified disparity, preventing critically ill Black patients from accessing needed care.
\fs32 \super 61
\fs24 \nosupersub  In an adaptive documentation context, a similar bias could lead to the system allocating fewer supportive care resources or generating less comprehensive care plans for patients from marginalized groups.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Improper Treatment Risk (Performance Bias):
\f0\b0  This bias arises when an AI model performs less accurately for certain demographic groups because of underrepresentation in the training data. A well-known example is the higher error rate of facial recognition algorithms for individuals with darker skin tones. This same principle applies directly to medicine, where AI systems for dermatological diagnosis have been found to be less accurate for patients with darker skin because the training datasets were disproportionately composed of images from lighter-skinned individuals.
\fs32 \super 61
\fs24 \nosupersub  An adaptive documentation system trained on biased data could be less accurate at interpreting the clinical notes or symptoms of underrepresented patient populations, leading to errors in the official record.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mitigation Strategies:
\f0\b0  Combating algorithmic bias requires a proactive and continuous effort. It is not a problem that can be solved once. Key strategies include 
\fs32 \super 63
\fs24 \nosupersub :\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl1
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Inclusive and Diverse Datasets:
\f0\b0  The most critical step is ensuring that training data is as representative as possible of the diverse patient populations the model will serve.\
\ls10\ilvl1
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Algorithm Audits and Fairness-Aware Design:
\f0\b0  Algorithms must be regularly audited to test their performance across different demographic groups. Fairness constraints can also be incorporated directly into the model's training process to optimize for equitable outcomes.\
\ls10\ilvl1
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Transparency and Explainability:
\f0\b0  Making AI models more transparent allows clinicians and auditors to better understand and detect potential biases in their outputs.\
\ls10\ilvl1
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Continuous Monitoring:
\f0\b0  After deployment, systems must be continuously monitored with feedback loops to identify and correct any new biases that emerge over time.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
