\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 4.4 Preserving Patient Agency in an AI-Mediated System\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 \
Beyond the legal and safety issues, the use of an autonomous documentation system raises deep ethical questions about the nature of patient agency and autonomy.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Challenge to Self-Agency:
\f0\b0  The concept of self-agency is intimately tied to the idea of a person's lived experience. A recent commentary argues that the proliferation of generative AI in healthcare creates an environment where medical decisions can be influenced by data that does not derive from or encompass this "person-lived experience".
\fs32 \super 65
\fs24 \nosupersub  An autonomously generated medical record, even if factually accurate according to clinical inputs, may fail to capture the patient's unique narrative, values, or interpretation of their illness. If the record is generated by a machine, and the patient's role is merely to correct its errors, it can be argued that their agency in constructing their own health story is diminished.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Complexity of Informed Consent:
\f0\b0  In a traditional encounter, a patient provides informed consent for a treatment or procedure. In an AI-mediated system, the nature of consent becomes more complex. For consent to be truly informed, the patient must understand the role that the AI is playing in their care, including how it documents information and how its outputs might influence clinical decisions.
\fs32 \super 59
\fs24 \nosupersub Adequately explaining the probabilistic, "black box" nature of a complex, adaptive AI system to a patient in a way that allows for genuine understanding is a profound communication and ethical challenge.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Primacy of Human Oversight:
\f0\b0  Patients themselves express a clear preference for maintaining human oversight in their care. A large international survey found that over 70% of patients preferred physician-led decision-making and explainable AI, even if it meant a slight compromise in diagnostic accuracy.
\fs32 \super 38
\fs24 \nosupersub  This finding underscores the ethical imperative to design systems that empower, rather than disenfranchise, both the patient and the clinician. The goal must be to ensure that the patient does not feel that their care is being dictated by an opaque and unaccountable algorithm, but that the technology serves as a tool to facilitate a richer, more accurate, and more collaborative relationship with their human care team.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The consistent message across the technical, legal, and ethical literature is that governance is not an afterthought but a foundational prerequisite. The development and deployment of an adaptive documentation system cannot follow a linear path of building the technology first and then attempting to solve the ethical and legal problems later. This approach is doomed to fail. Instead, it demands a co-design process where technical architects, clinical experts, legal counsel, ethicists, and patients collaborate from the very beginning. The governance framework\'97which defines accountability, mandates bias audits, establishes privacy protocols, and preserves human agency\'97is not a layer to be applied to a finished product. It is a set of core requirements that must fundamentally shape the system's architecture, functionality, and workflow from day one.\
\
